What could you have done differently during the planning stages of your project to make the execution easier?

Looking back on the planning phase, I definitely should have mapped out the HTML structure in closer coordination with my JavaScript DOM selectors from the start. For example,
 I wrote the logic to query and update the runtime clock (#dive-clock), but completely forgot to include the actual container element in the HTML markup.
 That created some unnecessary DOM manipulation bugs until I caught and fixed it. On the styling side, 
 pre-defining my CSS variable overrides for theme switching (like Deep Water Mode) before writing the JS toggle logic would have made the CSS implementation a lot smoother.


Were there any requirements that were difficult to implement? What do you think 
would make them easier to implement in future projects?

Honestly, setting up custom form validation with dynamic UI states was the trickiest part of the whole project. 
Trying to manage error spans, toggle classes on the parent .form-group containers, and give real-time feedback while 
blocking native form submissions meant I had to be super exact with my DOM traversal.
Next time, I’m definitely defining all my state classes (like .has-error, .is-valid, and .success-alert)
 in the CSS before writing the JS event listeners. It would’ve made debugging visual feedback way faster.




What would you add to, or change about your application if given more time?

